│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe slp-vectorizer produces invalid IR for the      │
│ provided reproducer, detected by the verifier with the message \"Instruction  │
│ does not dominate all uses!\" concerning two consecutive shufflevector        │
│ instructions on <4 x ptr>. The verifier reports that the first shuffle does   │
│ not dominate the second, meaning the use (second shuffle) is located earlier  │
│ in the program order (or in a block not dominated by the defining             │
│ instruction). This indicates the pass emitted a shuffle at an insertion point │
│ earlier than the definitions of its operand instructions, violating SSA       │
│ dominance rules.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe crash occurs immediately     │
│ after running slp-vectorizer and before any other transformation. No other    │
│ passes mutate the IR, so the faulty transformation must originate inside      │
│ SLPVectorizer. The offending IR pattern (two pointer shuffles, second using   │
│ the first) suggests a build-vector or shuffle finalization step mishandled    │
│ instruction ordering. The gather/build-vector logic generates shuffles        │
│ progressively, and finalize() in ShuffleInstructionBuilder emits the last     │
│ shuffle combining earlier shuffles. There is no adjustment of the IRBuilder's │
│ insertion point relative to the operand instructions before emitting this     │
│ final shuffle.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nWithin                             │
│ BoUpSLP::ShuffleInstructionBuilder::finalize(), we call                       │
│ createShuffle(InVectors.front(), InVectors.back(), CommonMask) (or            │
│ single-source variant) at the current IRBuilder insertion point. However, the │
│ insertion point may have been moved earlier (e.g., by surrounding logic such  │
│ as PHI handling, setInsertPointAfterBundle, or other manipulations) after the │
│ operand shuffles have already been created later in the same basic block.     │
│ finalize() lacks a dominance safeguard; it assumes the builder insertion      │
│ point already follows all operand instructions. Thus it can emit a shuffle    │
│ before its operand definitions, producing IR where a use precedes its         │
│ definition in the same block, triggering the verifier error.\nThe reproducer  │
│ involves pointer GEP-related gathers across a control-flow region, amplifying │
│ sensitivity to incorrect insertion point placement.\n\n4. Proposed Edit       │
│ Point(s):\nEdit SLPVectorizer.cpp at the start of                             │
│ ShuffleInstructionBuilder::finalize (just after setting IsFinalized) to       │
│ ensure the insertion point is advanced after all operand instructions in the  │
│ current block before emitting any new shuffle that references them. This      │
│ guarantees dominance.\n\nSuggested code to insert at line 13805 (after        │
│ 'IsFinalized = true;'):\n\n// Ensure the insertion point dominates all        │
│ operand instructions before\n// emitting the final shuffle(s). If the current │
│ insertion point precedes\n// any of the existing operand instructions in the  │
│ same basic block,\n// move it after the last such operand. This prevents      │
│ creating a shuffle\n// that uses values defined later, which would violate    │
│ dominance.\nif (Builder.GetInsertBlock()) {\n  Instruction *CurIP =           │
│ nullptr;\n  if (Builder.GetInsertPoint() !=                                   │
│ Builder.GetInsertBlock()->end())\n    CurIP = &*Builder.GetInsertPoint();\n   │
│ Instruction *LatestOperandInBlock = nullptr;\n  for (Value *Op : InVectors)   │
│ {\n    if (auto *OpI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Op)) {\n      if                 │
│ (OpI->getParent() == Builder.GetInsertBlock()) {\n        if                  │
│ (!LatestOperandInBlock || LatestOperandInBlock->comesBefore(OpI))\n           │
│ LatestOperandInBlock = OpI;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  if (LatestOperandInBlock  │
│ && CurIP && CurIP->comesBefore(LatestOperandInBlock)) {\n                     │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(LatestOperandInBlock->getNextNonDebugInstruction());\n │
│ } else if (LatestOperandInBlock && !CurIP) {\n    // No current IP (pointing  │
│ at end); still ensure we emit after operands.\n                               │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(LatestOperandInBlock->getNextNonDebugInstruction());\n │
│ }\n}\n\nThis adjustment is minimal, localized, and does not alter cost        │
│ modeling or other logic; it solely enforces SSA dominance for emitted         │
│ shuffles.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe invalid IR stems from finalize() emitting a  │
│ shuffle before its operand shuffles due to a stale/earlier insertion point.   │
│ Adding logic to advance the insertion point after all operand instructions in │
│ the active block ensures dominance and prevents generation of broken IR for   │
│ the reproducer and similar cases involving multi-step shuffle construction.   │
│ The fix is a targeted insertion at line 13805 in SLPVectorizer.cpp, aligning  │
│ shuffle emission with operand definition order without affecting other        │
│ vectorization decisions."})                                                   │
