│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The slp-vectorizer produces invalid IR for the provided reproducer, detected  │
│ by the verifier with the message "Instruction does not dominate all uses!"    │
│ concerning two consecutive shufflevector instructions on <4 x ptr>. The       │
│ verifier reports that the first shuffle does not dominate the second, meaning │
│ the use (second shuffle) is located earlier in the program order (or in a     │
│ block not dominated by the defining instruction). This indicates the pass     │
│ emitted a shuffle at an insertion point earlier than the definitions of its   │
│ operand instructions, violating SSA dominance rules.                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The crash occurs immediately after running slp-vectorizer and before any      │
│ other transformation. No other passes mutate the IR, so the faulty            │
│ transformation must originate inside SLPVectorizer. The offending IR pattern  │
│ (two pointer shuffles, second using the first) suggests a build-vector or     │
│ shuffle finalization step mishandled instruction ordering. The                │
│ gather/build-vector logic generates shuffles progressively, and finalize() in │
│ ShuffleInstructionBuilder emits the last shuffle combining earlier shuffles.  │
│ There is no adjustment of the IRBuilder's insertion point relative to the     │
│ operand instructions before emitting this final shuffle.                      │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ Within BoUpSLP::ShuffleInstructionBuilder::finalize(), we call                │
│ createShuffle(InVectors.front(), InVectors.back(), CommonMask) (or            │
│ single-source variant) at the current IRBuilder insertion point. However, the │
│ insertion point may have been moved earlier (e.g., by surrounding logic such  │
│ as PHI handling, setInsertPointAfterBundle, or other manipulations) after the │
│ operand shuffles have already been created later in the same basic block.     │
│ finalize() lacks a dominance safeguard; it assumes the builder insertion      │
│ point already follows all operand instructions. Thus it can emit a shuffle    │
│ before its operand definitions, producing IR where a use precedes its         │
│ definition in the same block, triggering the verifier error.                  │
│ The reproducer involves pointer GEP-related gathers across a control-flow     │
│ region, amplifying sensitivity to incorrect insertion point placement.        │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit SLPVectorizer.cpp at the start of ShuffleInstructionBuilder::finalize    │
│ (just after setting IsFinalized) to ensure the insertion point is advanced    │
│ after all operand instructions in the current block before emitting any new   │
│ shuffle that references them. This guarantees dominance.                      │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested code to insert at line 13805 (after 'IsFinalized = true;'):         │
│                                                                               │
│ // Ensure the insertion point dominates all operand instructions before       │
│ // emitting the final shuffle(s). If the current insertion point precedes     │
│ // any of the existing operand instructions in the same basic block,          │
│ // move it after the last such operand. This prevents creating a shuffle      │
│ // that uses values defined later, which would violate dominance.             │
│ if (Builder.GetInsertBlock()) {                                               │
│   Instruction *CurIP = nullptr;                                               │
│   if (Builder.GetInsertPoint() != Builder.GetInsertBlock()->end())            │
│     CurIP = &*Builder.GetInsertPoint();                                       │
│   Instruction *LatestOperandInBlock = nullptr;                                │
│   for (Value *Op : InVectors) {                                               │
│     if (auto *OpI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Op)) {                              │
│       if (OpI->getParent() == Builder.GetInsertBlock()) {                     │
│         if (!LatestOperandInBlock || LatestOperandInBlock->comesBefore(OpI))  │
│           LatestOperandInBlock = OpI;                                         │
│       }                                                                       │
│     }                                                                         │
│   }                                                                           │
│   if (LatestOperandInBlock && CurIP &&                                        │
│ CurIP->comesBefore(LatestOperandInBlock)) {                                   │
│     Builder.SetInsertPoint(LatestOperandInBlock->getNextNonDebugInstruction() │
│ );                                                                            │
│   } else if (LatestOperandInBlock && !CurIP) {                                │
│     // No current IP (pointing at end); still ensure we emit after operands.  │
│     Builder.SetInsertPoint(LatestOperandInBlock->getNextNonDebugInstruction() │
│ );                                                                            │
│   }                                                                           │
│ }                                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ This adjustment is minimal, localized, and does not alter cost modeling or    │
│ other logic; it solely enforces SSA dominance for emitted shuffles.           │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The invalid IR stems from finalize() emitting a shuffle before its operand    │
│ shuffles due to a stale/earlier insertion point. Adding logic to advance the  │
│ insertion point after all operand instructions in the active block ensures    │
│ dominance and prevents generation of broken IR for the reproducer and similar │
│ cases involving multi-step shuffle construction. The fix is a targeted        │
│ insertion at line 13805 in SLPVectorizer.cpp, aligning shuffle emission with  │
│ operand definition order without affecting other vectorization decisions.     │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
